Chile's presidential race heads to runoff between communist and hard-right candidates
description: Jeannette Jara, 51, a communist and former labor minister representing Chile's center-left governing coalition, won 26.85% of votes with 99% counted – insufficient to win in the first round. Hard-right ex-lawmaker and devout Catholic Jose Antonio Kast, 59, secured more than 23.93%. A second round will take place on December 14.

headline: What is Europe's 'fair share' of climate action compared to other countries?
description: Europe produces only 6% of today's global greenhouse gas emissions, a point some politicians use to play down the continent's responsibility. Scientists counter that, looking at historical emissions, Europe still has far to go to meet the Paris Agreement.

headline: Photographer documents the Bataclan's slow rebirth after the 2015 Paris attacks
description: Vassili Feodoroff has photographed more than 40 concerts at the Bataclan since 2023. Ten years after the November 13 attacks, he has become a privileged witness to the slow but unmistakable resurrection of a venue that has rebuilt itself alongside its audience.

headline: London's 'mudlarks' scour the Thames for treasure
description: On the banks of the British capital's river, London's 'mudlarks' search for fragments of the past: ancient pottery, old coins, bone dice. These enthusiasts are less motivated by the value of the objects than by the stories they tell. Sometimes, their finds even end up in a museum, as is currently being shown in an exhibition at the London Museum.

headline: Euroclear, the Belgian institution managing frozen Russian assets that will 'not rule out' suing the EU
description: Euroclear, a little-known but central player in Europe's financial system, holds €193 billion in frozen Russian assets that, since the invasion of Ukraine, have drawn intense scrutiny. Its director general, Valérie Urbain, warns that confiscation – illegal under international law – would weaken Europe's position.

headline: COP30: 'Those drawn to China's environmental push should keep a few facts in mind'
description: China is presenting itself as the leader in the renewable energy economy, positioning itself against the United States, which remains entrenched in fossil fuels. Yet, this transition has proven misleading, writes Pascal Riché in his column for Le Monde.
